  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks aimed at combating money laundering. These are primarily established through international conventions, treaties, and guidelines set by global organizations. Here are some key examples:\n\n1. **United Nations Conventions**:\n   - **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Also known as the Vienna Convention, it was one of the first international efforts to address money laundering, particularly in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions to combat money laundering associated with organized crime.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: Also called the Merida Convention, it emphasizes measures to prevent and combat money laundering linked to corruption.\n\n2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**:\n   - The FATF is an intergovernmental organization that sets global standards for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats. Its **40 Recommendations** provide a comprehensive framework for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures. Countries are evaluated on their compliance with these recommendations.\n\n3. **European Union Directives**:\n   - The EU has issued several Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs) that member states must transpose into national law. These directives align with FATF standards and address issues like beneficial ownership transparency, digital currencies, and enhanced due diligence.\n\n4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**:\n   - The Basel Committee, part of the Bank for International Settlements (BIS), has issued principles for banks to implement effective AML measures, focusing on customer due diligence and reporting suspicious activities.\n\n5. **Regional Bodies**:\n   - Organizations like the **Egmont Group** (a network of financial intelligence units) and regional FATF-style bodies (e.g., the **Asia/Pacific Group on Money Laundering** and the **Caribbean Financial Action Task Force**) support the implementation of AML measures globally.\n\nWhile these frameworks provide guidelines, it is up to individual countries to adopt and enforce laws in line with these international standards. Compliance is often monitored through mutual evaluations and peer reviews conducted by organizations like the FATF.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
